Maybe I’ll take notes on everything that's been completed to keep things organized. It seems like having a clear overview will help me see what’s left and what’s done. Alright, let's get started!\"}]}"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Terceiro bloco concluído: S4-S6 já está auditado e os ficheiros foram criados em `reviews\\tobias_review_29mar`:\n\n- `10_s4_review.md`\n- `11_s5_review.md`\n- `12_s6_review.md`\n- `zz_blockB_notes.md`\n\nResumo desse bloco:\n\n- **S4**: arquitectura boa, com foco claro em `.jpg + .json` lado a lado, mas com gaps **P0** em nomenclatura, schema, dedupe e licença.\n- **S5**: a divisão `narrative_segmenter -> asset_matcher -> visual_director` foi validada; o `running_summary` faz sentido, mas precisa de schema rígido para não virar acoplamento opaco.\n- **S6**: a filosofia está correcta (“executa, não decide”), mas o setor ainda está incompleto sem definição fechada de `browser skills`, `portrait_manager` e `prompt_builder`.\n- **Notas globais**: ficaram registadas contradições exactas entre docs centrais e docs de setor, especialmente em:\n  - `docs/04_BRANCH_ARCHITECTURE.md`\n  - `docs/09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md`\n  - `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\n\nAgora já tenho os 3 blocos. Vou fazer a consolidação final e gerar:\n- `17_architecture_review_v2.md`\n- `18_skills_inventory_v2.md`\n- `19_tools_inventory_v2.md`\n- `20_implementation_roadmap_v2.md`\n- `21_summary_v2.md`","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0393662c76835c040169c934a1dcc48191bf78e537c4a4321e\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_yfLZWIG4h4wOJfDHST69x4Tj|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934a8e30c819186c5d805d365d2c7","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/reviews/tobias_review_29mar/zz_blockA_notes.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/reviews/tobias_review_29mar/zz_blockA_notes.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_eGtY2052g8oqYbyf7dQn76yl|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934a8e31881919aaf77d65f7be714","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/reviews/tobias_review_29mar/zz_blockB_notes.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/reviews/tobias_review_29mar/zz_blockB_notes.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_e8BXk9Zx4v4lbEMGBeOvlsmj|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934a8e3248191bd82c0f2b2763dde","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/reviews/tobias_review_29mar/zz_blockC_notes.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/reviews/tobias_review_29mar/zz_blockC_notes.md\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_9eQTesqkpygy09ZeybX6lEXe|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934a8e32c8191a38fc30a42be61e8","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/reviews/tobias_night_review_26mar/00_summary.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/reviews/tobias_night_review_26mar/00_summary.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":1400,"output":564,"cacheRead":41472,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":43436,"cost":{"input":0.0035,"output":0.00846,"cacheRead":0.010367999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.022328}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774793882930,"responseId":"resp_0393662c76835c040169c9349cee0c8191a5d491d969927911"}}
{"type":"message","id":"8838f6d0","parentId":"97581b2b","timestamp":"2026-03-29T14:18:16.059Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_yfLZWIG4h4wOJfDHST69x4Tj|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934a8e30c819186c5d805d365d2c7","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Block A Notes — 29 Mar 2026\n\n## Ficheiros lidos (estimativa)\n- Reviews antigas: 5\n- Docs centrais/ligados ao escopo principal: ~8 lidos directamente + referência cruzada parcial a outros\n- Workspace mirror PM: 3 ficheiros centrais lidos\n- Workspace mirror S1: 3 ficheiros de supervisor lidos + material já auditado em 26 Mar\n- Workspace mirror S2: 3 ficheiros de supervisor lidos\n- Workspace mirror S3: 3 ficheiros de supervisor lidos\n- Total efectivo consultado nesta ronda: ~25 ficheiros\n- Total contextual considerado com reviews antigas + referências: ~40-50 artefactos\n\n---\n\n## Issues principais\n1. **Terminologia ainda híbrida no projecto**\n   - Docs centrais novos falam em Setor / Supervisor / SM-S# / Operador\n   - Mas paths, mirrors e docs antigos continuam com Branch / BM / agent(s)\n\n2. **VO continua sem workspace_mirror operativo**\n   - bloqueio real para implementação do orquestrador\n\n3. **PM depende de skill principal não implementada (`read_pub`)**\n   - sem isso, o PM não opera autonomamente\n\n4. **S1 continua bloqueado por validators não implementados**\n   - `screenplay_validator`\n   - `polish_validator`\n\n5. **S2 está em duas versões ao mesmo tempo**\n   - doc oficial e mirror divergem em skills, naming, paths e checkpoints\n\n6. **S3 continua com deduplicação e validação insuficientes**\n   - especialmente crítico para atmosphere / era_context / entidades implícitas\n\n---\n\n## Skills mencionadas\n\n### PM\n- read_pub\n- job_builder\n- job_validator\n- override_parser\n- pub_row_normalizer\n\n### VO\n- job_validator\n- script_fetch_and_lock\n- video_dir_initializer\n- sector_dispatcher\n- checkpoint_resolver\n- final_report_builder\n- retry_classifier\n- lock_recovery_manager\n- status_aggregator\n\n### S1\n- screenplay_validator\n- polish_validator\n- scene_bible_schema_validator\n- checkpoint_writer / checkpoint_validator\n\n### S2\n- tts_generator\n- audio_transcriber\n- timestamp_aligner\n- bible_updater\n- ratio_calculator\n- alignment_confidence_checker\n- scene_bible_lock_manager\n\n### S3\n- bible_updater\n- entity_output_validator\n- entity_deduplicator\n- searchability_scorer\n- cross_identifier_consistency_checker\n\n---\n\n## Tools OpenClaw / integrações mencionadas\n- `read`\n- `write`\n- `exec`\n- `process`\n- Google Sheets API\n- Google Drive API\n- Telegram reporting\n- Gemini TTS via KMS\n- WhisperX local\n- OpenRouter\n- filesystem/checkpoints\n\n---\n\n## Contradições detectadas (com paths exactos)\n\n### 1. Terminologia nova vs antiga no PM\n- `docs/10_PRODUCTION_MANAGER.md`\n  - usa lógica nova de setores/operadores\n- `workspace_mirror/production_manager/IDENTITY.md`\n  - ainda diz “não executas produção (isso são os branches)”\n\n### 2. Hierarquia nova vs arquitectura antiga transversal\n- `docs/09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md`\n  - regista em 28 Mar: `branches -> setores`, `Branch Managers -> Supervisores de Setor`\n- `docs/04_BRANCH_ARCHITECTURE.md`\n  - continua a estruturar o projecto inteiro em `branches/`, `operadores/agents`, etc.\n\n### 3. VO pressuposto vs VO inexistente no mirror\n- `docs/11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md`\n  - aponta para `workspace_mirror/video_orchestrator/`\n- No escopo lido, esse espelho não estava presente\n\n### 4. S1 checkpoint naming inconsistente\n- `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`\n  - usa `b1_step1_screenplay.json`, `b1_complete.json`\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/01_pre_production/RULES.md`\n  - usa `s1_step1_screenplay.json`, `s1_complete.json`\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/01_pre_production/TOOLS.md`\n  - reforça `s1_step{N}_{name}.json`\n\n### 5. S2 versão doc != versão mirror\n- `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\n  - skills principais: `tts_generator`, `audio_transcriber`, `timing_extractor`\n  - paths: `b2_audio/...`\n  - checkpoints: `b2_step...`\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/02_audio/IDENTITY.md`\n  - skills: `tts_generator`, `audio_transcriber`, `timestamp_aligner`, `bible_updater`\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/02_audio/TOOLS.md`\n  - paths: `s2_audio/...`\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/02_audio/RULES.md`\n  - checkpoints: `s2_step...`\n\n### 6. Nomenclatura residual estrutural\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/01_pre_production/...`\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/02_audio/...`\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/03_visual_planning/...`\n- Mesmo quando o conteúdo fala em Setor/SM-S#, o path estrutural ainda conserva `branches`\n\n### 7. `agent/agents` residual material em docs centrais e sector docs\n- `docs/03_PIPELINE_MAP.md`\n  - ainda usa “Screenplay Agent”, “fix agent”, “candidatas a agentes” no mapeamento do V3\n- `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`, `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`, `docs/branches/03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md`\n  - ainda usam “agente/sub-agente” em pontos onde a nomenclatura macro já migrou para operador\n\n---\n\n## Julgamento global do bloco A\n- **PM:** melhor especificado, ainda não autónomo\n- **VO:** mais maduro no desenho, ainda sem corpo operativo\n- **S1:** forte conceptualmente, validators continuam blocker\n- **S2:** melhor desenho técnico, mas documentalmente partido em duas versões\n- **S3:** inteligente e promissor, mas ainda frágil em validação/deduplicação/searchability\n\nSe fosse priorizar brutalmente:\n1. **P0:** PM `read_pub`, VO mirror, S1 validators, S2 unificação canónica, S2 bible_updater\n2. **P1:** limpeza de nomenclatura / contratos / checkpoints / paths\n3. **P2:** optimizações de criatividade, scoring e refinamento\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774793896028}}
{"type":"message","id":"b33b658b","parentId":"8838f6d0","timestamp":"2026-03-29T14:18:16.092Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_eGtY2052g8oqYbyf7dQn76yl|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934a8e31881919aaf77d65f7be714","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Block B Notes — S4 + S5 + S6\n\n## Resumo executivo\nBloco B está **arquiteturalmente promissor**, mas ainda com desalinhamentos documentais suficientes para criar implementação inconsistente se não forem fechados agora.\n\n### Estado por setor\n- **S4**: forte e relativamente maduro; precisa fechar nomenclatura, schema e licença.\n- **S5**: decisão estrutural excelente; precisa fechar contratos entre bloco/momento/cena e schema do `running_summary`.\n- **S6**: filosofia certa, mas ainda depende de 3 componentes críticos em aberto (`browser skills`, `portrait_manager`, `prompt_builder`).\n\n---\n\n## Top findings transversais\n\n## 1. O maior problema não é ideia; é contrato\nNos três setores, o risco principal já não é “a arquitetura está errada”. O risco é:\n- docs globais e docs de setor a apontarem para artefactos diferentes;\n- workspaces espelho ainda conterem resíduos de versões antigas;\n- componentes downstream dependerem de nomes/campos/paths que ainda não estão congelados.\n\n## 2. Resíduos antigos relevantes\n### S4\n- `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md` ainda fala em `metadata.json` por entidade, contrariando `docs/branches/04_ASSET_RESEARCH.md`.\n- outputs/checkpoints usam mistura de `character_searcher.json`, `characters.json`, `b4_*`, `s4_*`.\n\n### S5\n- `docs/09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md` ainda descreve o S5 antigo (`style_guide_enforcer`, `asset_selector`).\n- `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md` ainda descreve `style_decisions.json`, `asset_selections.json`, `generation_briefs.json` em vez da estrutura nova por `blocks/kits/briefs`.\n- `workspace_mirror/branches/05_visual_direction/TOOLS.md` ainda opera muito por cena, não por momento visual.\n\n### S6\n- `docs/04_BRANCH_ARCHITECTURE.md` e `docs/09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md` ainda descrevem o S6 antigo (`portrait_generator`, `ai_image_director`, `image_generator`, `image_animator`).\n- `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md` ainda descreve a árvore antiga de S6.\n- o caso `keep_previous` não está absorvido em S6.\n\n---\n\n## Nomenclatura — problemas centrais\n\n### Prefixos\nExiste mistura entre:\n- `b4_asset_research` / `b4_*`\n- `s4_asset_research` / `s4_*`\n\nIsto aparece sobretudo em S4 e precisa ser congelado. A documentação global aponta mais para `s#_`, enquanto a doc específica de S4 ainda carrega `b4_`.\n\n### Outputs por tipo\nExiste mistura entre output por categoria e output por agente:\n- `characters.json` vs `character_searcher.json`\n- `maps_diagrams.json` vs `map_diagram_searcher.json`\n\n### Slugs\nMistura entre:\n- `erwin_rommel`\n- `general-george-s-patton`\n\nOu underscore ou hyphen — hoje não está fechado.\n\n---\n\n## Dependências e acoplamentos críticos\n\n## S4 -> S5\nS5 depende de S4 produzir metadata que seja simultaneamente:\n- legível por humano;\n- usável por matching automatizado.\n\nHoje isso ainda está a meio caminho. `tags` + `how_to_use` ajudam, mas faltam **flags estruturadas**.\n\n## S5 -> S6\nS6 depende de `compiled_visual_brief.json` ser claro e executável. O ponto crítico aqui é que S5 já pensa por **momento visual**, mas parte do mirror/contexto ainda pensa por **cena**.\n\n## S5/S6 -> S7\nA fronteira composição vs geração está razoável em teoria, mas ainda precisa contrato forte para:\n- `composition`\n- `keep_previous`\n- `img2video`\n- motion/intenção vs implementação TSX.\n\n---\n\n## Priorização global\n\n## P0 — resolver antes de implementação séria\n1. Congelar nomenclatura de diretórios/checkpoints/outputs (`b#` vs `s#`, nomes de JSONs).\n2. Atualizar docs globais para refletir S5 e S6 novos.\n3. Formalizar schema de JSON individual por asset em S4.\n4. Formalizar schema de `compiled_visual_brief.json` e `running_summary.json` em S5.\n5. Definir contrato de `browser skills`, `portrait_manager` e `prompt_builder` em S6.\n6. Resolver explicitamente `keep_previous` no handoff S5 -> S6/S7.\n\n## P1\n7. Criar validadores determinísticos para S4/S5/S6.\n8. Criar taxonomy de QA / rejection / retry.\n9. Estruturar melhor dedupe e licenciamento em S4.\n\n## P2\n10. Pensar em métricas e telemetry transversal dos setores visuais.\n\n---\n\n## Sugestões transversais\n\n### 1. Criar schemas formais\nSugestão prática: criar um pequeno pacote `schemas/` com pelo menos:\n- `s4_asset_json.schema.json`\n- `s4_entity_summary.schema.json`\n- `s5_block.schema.json`\n- `s5_kit.schema.json`\n- `s5_visual_brief.schema.json`\n- `s5_running_summary.schema.json`\n- `s6_compiled_output.schema.json`\n\n### 2. Separar texto livre de campos operacionais\nSempre que um campo vai alimentar automação posterior, preferir estrutura. Exemplos:\n- além de `how_to_use`, ter `usage_flags` em S4;\n- além de `reason`, ter `rejection_codes` em S6 QA;\n- além de resumo textual, ter `asset_usage_count` e `canonical_references` em S5.\n\n### 3. Atualizar primeiro os docs centrais\nAntes de implementar agentes/skills, vale alinhar pelo menos:\n- `docs/04_BRANCH_ARCHITECTURE.md`\n- `docs/09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md`\n- `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\n\nPorque hoje estes três ainda são a principal fonte de ambiguidade sistémica.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusão\nO bloco B está forte em visão de sistema. Os problemas encontrados são, em grande parte, de **consolidação arquitetural** e não de falta de qualidade conceitual.\n\nSe eu resumisse em uma frase:\n\n> S4 está quase pronto para ser transformado em contratos; S5 está arquiteturalmente certo mas precisa congelar interfaces; S6 está estrategicamente certo mas ainda precisa ser especificado para existir de verdade.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774793896060}}
{"type":"message","id":"82e9866f","parentId":"b33b658b","timestamp":"2026-03-29T14:18:16.125Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_e8BXk9Zx4v4lbEMGBeOvlsmj|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934a8e3248191bd82c0f2b2763dde","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Block C Notes — S7 + S8 + S9 + S10\n\n## Síntese executiva\n- **S7**: melhor coerência conceptual do bloco, mas com drift de schema/skills entre spec e mirror.\n- **S8**: princípio técnico excelente (resolver gatekeeper), mas mirror ainda descreve engines/JSON e lettering ainda não está bem separado em 2 passos.\n- **S9**: maior concentração de contradições. Reviewer set, naming de ficheiros, resolução e ownership inter-setor ainda não estão fechados.\n- **S10**: desenho mais simples e robusto, mas precisa alinhar estrutura de checkpoints/directórios e não exagerar o claim de monitoring coberto.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-cutting findings\n\n### 1. Drift entre spec definitiva e workspace_mirror\nIsto aparece em todos os setores do bloco C.\n\n#### Casos mais claros\n- `docs/branches/07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md` vs `workspace_mirror/branches/07_scene_composition/AGENTS.md`\n- `docs/branches/08_POST_PRODUCTION.md` vs `workspace_mirror/branches/08_post_production/AGENTS.md`\n- `docs/branches/09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md` vs `workspace_mirror/branches/09_assembly_render/AGENTS.md`\n- `docs/branches/10_FINALIZATION.md` vs `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\n\n### 2. Nomenclatura ainda não estabilizada\nResíduos relevantes:\n- `scene_id` vs `moment_id`\n- `duration_frames` vs `duration_ms`\n- `SfxLayer.tsx` vs `SFXComplete.tsx`\n- `LetteringLayer.tsx` vs `LettBatch_N.tsx`\n- `music_engine/sfx_engine/lettering_engine` vs `music_tsx/sfx_tsx/lettering_tsx`\n- `narration_reviewer/soundtrack_reviewer` vs `music_reviewer/sfx_reviewer`\n\n### 3. Resíduo documental de versões anteriores\nO mirror ainda mistura 3 paradigmas:\n- pipeline manifest/JSON-first\n- pipeline TSX-first\n- naming antigo herdado de V3 / fase intermédia\n\n### 4. “agents” vs “operadores”\nMesmo depois da actualização terminológica em `docs/09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md`, o mirror continua com `agents/` em todos os setores do bloco. Não é grave por si só, mas mostra que a limpeza terminológica não foi concluída.\n\n---\n\n## Prioridades globais\n\n### P0 — resolver antes de implementação séria\n1. **Congelar naming canónico** de ficheiros, reviewers, skills e schemas.\n2. **Atualizar os AGENTS.md do mirror** para baterem 1:1 com as specs finais.\n3. **Criar schemas JSON canónicos** por planner/reviewer/skill.\n4. **Fechar ownership inter-setor**:\n   - quem gera `SoundtrackLayer.tsx`\n   - qual nome final do ficheiro SFX\n   - qual estrutura final do lettering\n5. **Corrigir a contradição de resolução no S9** (1920x1080 vs 1080x1920).\n\n### P1\n6. Fechar integração operacional de `audio_sync_checker` e `audio_levels_checker`.\n7. Fechar `lettering_style_planner` como componente explícito ou remover da spec.\n8. Fechar convenção única de checkpoints (global vs dentro do setor).\n9. Declarar policy de idempotência em S10 (upload/sheet/report).\n\n### P2\n10. Melhorar catálogos/fallbacks por conta.\n11. Adicionar validadores auxiliares para manifests e contratos inter-setor.\n12. Preparar observability mais real se quiserem substituir S11 de vez no médio prazo.\n\n---\n\n## Recomendações globais\n\n### Recomendação 1 — Contract Freeze\nCriar uma camada explícita de contratos em algo como:\n- `contracts/s7/*.schema.json`\n- `contracts/s8/*.schema.json`\n- `contracts/s9/*.schema.json`\n- `contracts/s10/*.schema.json`\n\nIsto reduz o drift entre prompt, spec e skill Python.\n\n### Recomendação 2 — Mirror Cleanup Sprint\nFazer um sprint curto só para alinhar:\n- `AGENTS.md`\n- prompts\n- nomes de ficheiros\n- output examples\n\nSem isso, qualquer implementação corre risco de materializar a versão errada.\n\n### Recomendação 3 — Adapter layer temporária\nSe quiserem implementar já sem reescrever tudo, criar adapters explícitos:\n- old prompt output -> canonical schema\n- old file names -> canonical file names\n\nMas isto deve ser temporário, porque aumenta debt.\n\n---\n\n## Mapa rápido por setor\n\n### S7\n- Força: arquitectura criativa/técnica muito boa\n- Fraqueza: schema drift forte\n- Risco central: implementar skills contra prompts errados\n\n### S8\n- Força: resolver gatekeeper é excelente\n- Fraqueza: lettering e outputs ainda não estabilizados\n- Risco central: mistura de conteúdo/estilo e engines vs TSX\n\n### S9\n- Força: defesa técnica em profundidade\n- Fraqueza: maior inconsistência documental do bloco\n- Risco central: montar/revisar contra ficheiros e reviewers errados\n\n### S10\n- Força: simples e determinístico\n- Fraqueza: pouca materialização e idempotência pouco explicitada\n- Risco central: duplicações / estrutura inconsistente / overclaim de monitoring\n\n---\n\n## Julgamento final do bloco C\nO bloco C está **forte em arquitectura de alto nível** e bastante melhor do que um pipeline monolítico tradicional. O problema não é falta de ideias; é que a documentação ainda contém **camadas temporais diferentes**. Antes de implementar pesado, vale muito alinhar os contratos. Especialmente em S9.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774793896093}}
{"type":"message","id":"6dc08fd5","parentId":"82e9866f","timestamp":"2026-03-29T14:18:16.169Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_9eQTesqkpygy09ZeybX6lEXe|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934a8e32c8191a38fc30a42be61e8","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# 00_summary.md\n\n## Tobias Night Review — Executive Summary\n**Date:** 27 Mar 2026\n**Scope reviewed:** Production Manager, Video Orchestrator, Branch 1 (Pre-Production), Branch 2 (Audio), Branch 3 (Visual Planning), and general architecture docs.\n\n---\n\n## What I reviewed\n\n### Review files produced\n1. `01_pm_review.md`\n2. `02_vo_review.md`\n3. `03_b1_review.md`\n4. `04_b2_review.md`\n5. `05_b3_review.md`\n6. `06_architecture_review.md`\n7. `07_skills_inventory.md`\n8. `08_tools_inventory.md`\n9. `09_implementation_roadmap.md`\n\n### Exact output folder\n`C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_night_review_26mar\\`\n\n---\n\n## Quantos ficheiros analisei\n\n### Count used for this review pass\nUsing the per-review counts from each component review:\n- PM review: **16**\n- VO review: **6** source elements\n- B1 review: **18**\n- B2 review: **19**\n- B3 review: **56**\n- Architecture review: **13**\n\n### Consolidated total\n- **128 analyzed source items**\n\n### Important note\nThis total contains **intentional overlap** across reviews (general docs were reread in multiple component-specific passes). So it is best interpreted as:\n- **128 review touches / analyzed items**\nnot\n- 128 unique physical files.\n\nThat overlap was acceptable and useful because each subagent read the shared docs through a different component lens.\n\n---\n\n## Quantas skills identifiquei\n\nFrom the consolidated inventory:\n- **37 consolidated skills**\n\n### Breakdown\n- **9 P0 / blocking**\n- **16 P1 / high priority**\n- **12 P2 / later / optimization**\n\n### Most critical missing skills\n- `read_pub`\n- `screenshot_validator`\n- `polish_validator`\n- `tts_generator`\n- `audio_transcriber`\n- `timestamp_aligner`\n- `bible_updater`\n- `job_validator`\n- `branch_orchestrator`\n\n---\n\n## Quantos tools identifiquei\n\nFrom the consolidated tooling inventory:\n- **25 tooling surfaces**\n\n### Breakdown\n- **6 OpenClaw-native core tools already available**\n- **6 required external APIs / services**\n- **5 local runtimes / executors**\n- **8 operational wrappers / tool contracts still needed**\n\n### Most critical tooling/contracts missing\n- Google Sheets wrapper/tool contract\n- Gemini TTS wrapper/tool contract\n- WhisperX wrapper/tool contract\n- scene_bible I/O / locking contract\n- OpenRouter dispatch contract for B3\n- checkpoint contract\n- structured error/escalation contract\n\n---\n\n## Estado geral por componente\n\n### Production Manager\n**Verdict:** conceptually solid, operationally incomplete.\n\nThe PM is one of the clearer parts of the architecture, but it still depends critically on `read_pub` and lacks strong override expiry, data validation and auditability.\n\n### Video Orchestrator\n**Verdict:** role is right, implementation substrate is not ready.\n\nVO is currently more specification than executable design. The biggest blocker is the lack of a real protocol for VO ↔ Branch Manager invocation and status handling.\n\n### B1 — Pre-Production\n**Verdict:** strongest branch in current scope.\n\nB1 is the best candidate to implement first. The design is disciplined, the agents are mostly well-scoped, and the leverage is high. The big blockers are missing validators and incomplete builder/orchestration docs.\n\n### B2 — Audio\n**Verdict:** strong architecture, big execution gap.\n\nB2 looks good in principle, but it is not ready. Too much depends on unimplemented wrappers, unvalidated V3 reuse and weakly specified shared-state handling.\n\n### B3 — Visual Planning\n**Verdict:** promising but riskier than it looks.\n\nB3 has a sophisticated structure, but it still needs output validation, deduplication hardening, explicit model choice and tighter grounding to avoid becoming a hallucination engine that pollutes B4.\n\n### General architecture\n**Verdict:** the conceptual architecture is ahead of the contract architecture.\n\nThis is the central pattern that showed up everywhere.\n\n---\n\n## Top 5 issues mais importantes\n\n### 1. **Interfaces and contracts are weaker than the component philosophy**\nThe architecture explains roles well, but often fails to explain exact payloads, ownership, invocation and failure semantics.\n\n### 2. **Video Orchestrator is underspecified where it matters most**\nIts role is clear, but its actual operational protocol is not. That makes it dangerous to implement too early.\n\n### 3. **scene_bible is central but still not protected enough**\nMultiple branches depend on reading/writing it, but locking, merging, atomic writes and ownership are not hardened.\n\n### 4. **The deterministic skill layer is missing**\nA lot of the system still assumes critical skills already exist. They do not.\n\n### 5. **B2 and B3 look more production-ready than they actually are**\nBoth are good specs, but operationally they still hide substantial unresolved complexity.\n\n---\n\n## Top 5 sugestões de melhoria\n\n### 1. **Harden schemas and invocation protocols before building more orchestration**\nWrite the contracts first. Especially:\n- PM job artifact\n- scene_bible\n- B3 compiled_entities\n- checkpoints\n- VO ↔ BM invocation\n\n### 2. **Build the deterministic substrate before the orchestrator layer**\nPrioritize:\n- `read_pub`\n- B1 validators\n- B2 wrappers\n- `bible_updater`\n- schema validation\n\n### 3. **Implement B1 first as the first truly real branch**\nIt is the strongest mix of leverage, clarity, and low cost.\n\n### 4. **Treat scene_bible I/O as shared infrastructure, not a helper**\nIt needs explicit lock/merge/versioning semantics.\n\n### 5. **Stop deferring key model/tool decisions**\nEspecially in B3. Pick defaults now, benchmark later. Deferred decisions are implementation debt.\n\n---\n\n## Overall note on documentation quality\n\n### Score: **7.8 / 10**\n\n### Why this is a strong score\nBecause the docs are:\n- serious\n- intentional\n- system-aware\n- much better than average agent-architecture documentation\n- clearly shaped by real production pain from V3\n\n### Why it is not higher\nBecause there is still too much gap between:\n- **role clarity** and **runtime contract clarity**\n- **high-level architecture** and **implementation substrate**\n- **beautiful branch decomposition** and **real deterministic tooling**\n\nIn other words:\n**the docs are good enough to guide a system, but not yet good enough to guarantee a low-friction implementation.**\n\n---\n\n## Final conclusion\n\nThe project is in a good place strategically.\n\nThe architecture is not fake. The thought is real. The separation of responsibilities is good. The hierarchy makes sense. The branch design is mostly intelligent.\n\nBut the next step is no longer more ideation.\n\nThe next step is to:\n1. harden contracts\n2. build the deterministic skills\n3. implement B1 first\n4. bring B2 and B3 into reality carefully\n5. only then let VO become the real orchestrator\n\nIf you do that in the right order, this can become a real operating system for the department.\n\nIf you skip that order and jump too early into orchestration polish, you'll create a lot of elegant-looking integration debt.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774793896125}}
{"type":"message","id":"8a6ed803","parentId":"6dc08fd5","timestamp":"2026-03-29T14:18:34.362Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Planning file creation**\n\nI need to create 5 files. First, I should read the filenames to count how many files are already in the folder. I wonder if using an execution count to review the files would be sufficient. I’m thinking I should keep my plan concise yet detailed based on my notes. It’s important to proceed carefully, ensuring I cover everything without missing any details. Let's figure out the best approach to do this!","thinkingSignature":"{\"id\":\"rs_0393662c76835c040169c934b38f24819195f15d2a287ea4da\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABpyTS3t7OnFBE4Zb-3v60KY7Mw-MqXpWXFmbw5bXEhJ3raRCmCOxNAwMTfaV9edl01QHgJ0z5V5VqEOXFoZeczSEobU15QGQV3SpyrA3x5BH5S4eLx_cibHZ1zdBtyEdNaWJdyEnih5dVFkQ6ecqsSAB9dxnHKrXvYaqeebJCigNEDCzrDIHY1aCxJcIIAk8DEmRwPFmOlJ39bNeZgOKHxmpj2ez3Loz1D30jKleyBszgFmLIwvFvrxQyfqPwlsWf4hmqXc-vTb_L5w6ZNRbE5qyjWVzr8kPV1EahJjjmHKdYn80eHWPHfqMM9SAIiWnWginMd_BvWJ0S07oxghMuhbMNZzO3K0a1T0PFG49sAXc5ZISr6TGuO2E2S04qXenOl3NGIq3nfXTMARUFy491g0GAmAQqi8zJv-xCQxQHD5wNsWUHI2w2UNfs9iQrdkFS4TRG_2Mos5JpVzLr21M5uelnekcR4w554x_GsveuaraDBd6MS_h5LUrwh52HmcxgQLCklcvJfmhELvflU3X4wQqK9C5JwtByF5lkoxGpJjDCAqsdzj60fluTdGcHLHveisCW3gxlIXa4y_00T8NhzOeV8jpo4k1sdLq2_HuEgwuxlp3OztDwW6ohbLTn_azIRyH3AixBFKXOY7mz61CKd-nQrOV5G2VVy-S7gBvKBT84tJ0lYahuEvwelMTWEgKWwPPxp-Ac25gD3r0O6GF0okUYAdV3i29A4xBHXOnNktclbN-JxGoNtX__WmJkvs3rbMua8V5IDfpKZqbgJk6ED3FMkzjsVQrA0jrunjD9G0J894HQbXrZR6ohA3miFrMN2GyomMPgcJsKNG-7Sawog6oCTbEvboD-Bctp_4jWbxqVzlmPwt93Pg0ip9S9lpCxikX9IPzyOACpTTkz7iSVOQcWKNYFZpQHS4IM8CLPdgUyd9SvHq2cNn5A3y8gjsIESEmIZtFTjWYmSNnDu-ou2E6c7Xs2FNm7oVBr1YOwkiF8ybIRi3CZQ2LKIsIk_gu0xOHivVbqLq9yL15z5CUjBlSlK3Q==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Planning file creation**\\n\\nI need to create 5 files. First, I should read the filenames to count how many files are already in the folder. I wonder if using an execution count to review the files would be sufficient. I’m thinking I should keep my plan concise yet detailed based on my notes. It’s important to proceed carefully, ensuring I cover everything without missing any details. Let's figure out the best approach to do this!\"}]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_YWshpIpvUVCoZ2HeQXzbQszJ|fc_0393662c76835c040169c934b76b3881918b92c62a904cdb6c","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"$base='C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory';\n$review='C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar';\nWrite-Output '--- review files ---'; Get-ChildItem $review -File | Select-Object -ExpandProperty Name;\nWrite-Output '--- counts ---';\n\"docs_md=$((Get-ChildItem (Join-Path $base 'docs') -Recurse -File -Filter *.md | Measure-Object).Count)\";\n\"workspace_mirror_md=$((Get-ChildItem (Join-Path $base 'workspace_mirror') -Recurse -File -Filter *.md | Measure-Object).Count)\";\n\"accounts_yaml=$((Get-ChildItem (Join-Path $base 'accounts') -Recurse -File | Where-Object {$_.Extension -in '.yaml','.yml'} | Measure-Object).Count)\";\n\"old_review_files=$((Get-ChildItem (Join-Path $base 'reviews\\tobias_night_review_26mar') -File | Measure-Object).Count)\";\n\"new_review_files=$((Get-ChildItem $review -File | Measure-Object).Count)\";\nWrite-Output '--- nomenclature hits ---';\n$patterns=@('Branch','branches','BM-','agent ','agents/','Supervisor','Setor');\nforeach($p in $patterns){\n  $count=(Get-ChildItem $base -Recurse -File -Include *.md | Select-String -Pattern $p -SimpleMatch | Measure-Object).Count;\n  \"${p}=$count\";\n}","yieldMs":10000,"workdir":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"$base='C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory';\\n$review='C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\reviews\\\\tobias_review_29mar';\\nWrite-Output '--- review files ---'; Get-ChildItem $review -File | Select-Object -ExpandProperty Name;\\nWrite-Output '--- counts ---';\\n\\\"docs_md=$((Get-ChildItem (Join-Path $base 'docs') -Recurse -File -Filter *.md | Measure-Object).Count)\\\";\\n\\\"workspace_mirror_md=$((Get-ChildItem (Join-Path $base 'workspace_mirror') -Recurse -File -Filter *.md | Measure-Object).Count)\\\";\\n\\\"accounts_yaml=$((Get-ChildItem (Join-Path $base 'accounts') -Recurse -File | Where-Object {$_.Extension -in '.yaml','.yml'} | Measure-Object).Count)\\\";\\n\\\"old_review_files=$((Get-ChildItem (Join-Path $base 'reviews\\\\tobias_night_review_26mar') -File | Measure-Object).Count)\\\";\\n\\\"new_review_files=$((Get-ChildItem $review -File | Measure-Object).Count)\\\";\\nWrite-Output '--- nomenclature hits ---';\\n$patterns=@('Branch','branches','BM-','agent ','agents/','Supervisor','Setor');\\nforeach($p in $patterns){\\n  $count=(Get-ChildItem $base -Recurse -File -Include *.md | Select-String -Pattern $p -SimpleMatch | Measure-Object).Count;\\n  \\\"${p}=$count\\\";\\n}\",\"yieldMs\":10000,\"workdir\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":5844,"output":453,"cacheRead":43264,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":49561,"cost":{"input":0.014610000000000001,"output":0.006795,"cacheRead":0.010816,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.032221}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774793896170,"responseId":"resp_0393662c76835c040169c934a9e84481919dab497c778684d1"}}
